ðŸ“– **Description:**
    The `grub-glue-efi` command is a utility for creating EFI image files from a GRUB EFI core image file. It helps you package and prepare GRUB for UEFI systems. Basically, `grub-glue-efi` is a "glue" that attaches GRUB to your UEFI system.

âš™ï¸ **Options:**
    ðŸ”¹ `--dest-path=PATH`  --> ðŸ“ Specifies the destination path where the resulting EFI image file will be saved.
    ðŸ”¹ `--core-image=FILE`  --> ðŸ’¾ Specifies the GRUB EFI core image file. This file is like the heart of GRUB for your UEFI setup.
    ðŸ”¹ `--modules=MODULE1,MODULE2,...` --> ðŸ§© Specifies additional GRUB modules to include. These are like plugins that enhance GRUB's capabilities.

ðŸ›  **Examples:**

    $ grub-glue-efi --dest-path=grubx64.efi --core-image=core.img --modules="normal linux boot chain"

    ðŸ”¹ This command glues the `core.img` with the "normal linux boot chain" modules together and creates an EFI file named `grubx64.efi` in the current directory.

    $ grub-glue-efi --dest-path=/boot/efi/EFI/myos/grubx64.efi --core-image=core.img

    ðŸ”¹ This command glues the `core.img` to the path `/boot/efi/EFI/myos/grubx64.efi`, offering a cleaner path to your system's EFI folder.

âœ… **Simple Example:**

